		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message28418259">A wonderfully heart-warming movie with an realistic portrayal of the turmoil one faces when growing up. Even if one might not be able to relate to any of the somewhat corny characters (which I doubt), they still feel genuinely human. The tale of the Baron and Baroness augments the movie in a magical and heart-felt way without take away from its down to earth nature. Another lovely aspect of this movie is the relationships between people of different generations; their interactions are subtle but overflowing with emotions. It displays a profound and inexplicable quality shared by all human beings (please someone help me put this quality into words). <br />
<br />
The singing scene is indeed wonderful. It's one of my favorite scenes in any anime, not least because I love Country Roads. <br />
<br />
My complaints may be mute to all the connoisseurs here, but I think this movie is a bit <em>too</em> corny. There's only so much you can do with such a simple premise; Ghibli did that and then some more. They did a great job at spicing up the story with their signature magic, and even then it was still too cheesy and predictable. The kids' love troubles in the first half of the movie felt especially unnecessary. Overall, Mimi wo Sumaseba is an wonderful and satisfying, but somewhat corny, experience.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
